<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIES OF VIETNAM WAR</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 14:16:04 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
The Vietnam War overshadowed my entire childhood.  I was born in Feb. 1960 and as far back as I can remember the war was raging on.  I was a particularly astute child, so I was interested in what was happening.  My 4th grade teacher said that the war was wrong and I believed her.  Besides, my favorite rock groups were speaking out against the war, and as a child, you are easily influenced.  I made posters with my friends that featured peace signs and said &quot;Make Love Not War,&quot; although I now know that I didn't know the real meaning of that statement.  I have vivid memories of watching the war on the news, reading about it in the supplement the NY Times put out for school kids, and refusing to sing the national anthem at assembly.  I also remember the horror of the Kent State shootings and wondering if the police or national guard would start to shoot little kids.  My 4th grade teacher lost her job for speaking out against the war and that made me angry because I thought she was the only person treating us like we had a brain.  I didn't know anyone personally, who fought in Vietnam and I wished the whole thing never happened.  I am older now and I do think the war was a huge mistake on the part of our politicians, but I have never blamed the men &amp; women who served because they felt they were doing their duty when the country asked them to serve.    
